  "format": "A five-person snake draft (Joanna Robinson, Amanda, Chris, Sean, Katie Rich) of the most egregious Oscar snubs across seven categories — one year comes off the board per pick, so 35 years of Academy history get rewritten. It closes with Sean's interview with 'Sirāt' director Oliver Laxe. Note: the full 35-pick rosters weren't recapped on-air; below are the marquee, confidently-attributed picks.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "draft",
      "heading": "The teams",
      "draftOf": "the greatest Oscar snubs in history",
      "teams": [
        {
          "host": "Joanna Robinson",
          "picks": [
            {
              "title": "Mad Max: Fury Road",
              "year": 2015,
              "category": "Best Picture Winner Snub",
              "note": "The #1 overall pick — the snub of snubs. A true-blue genre classic that lost to Spotlight before the Academy learned to honor genre."
            },
            {
              "title": "Rebecca",
              "year": 1940,
              "category": "Best Director Winner Snub",
              "note": "Finally give Hitchcock a directing Oscar — over John Ford's The Grapes of Wrath. Takes 1940 (and His Girl Friday) off the board."
            },
            {
              "title": "In the Mood for Love",
              "year": 2000,
              "category": "Best Picture Nominee Snub (21st c.)",
              "note": "Submitted as international but never nominated — a generous read of the 2000 eligibility."
            },
            {
              "title": "Witness",
              "year": 1985,
              "category": "Best Actor Winner Snub",
              "note": "Give Harrison Ford the Oscar he deserved — taken from William Hurt."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "host": "Amanda Dobbins",
          "picks": [
            {
              "title": "The Social Network",
              "year": 2010,
              "category": "Best Picture Winner Snub",
              "note": "One of the great miscarriages of Oscar justice — lost to The King's Speech, and Fincher still has no Oscar."
            },
            {
              "title": "Malcolm X",
              "year": 1992,
              "category": "Best Actor Winner Snub",
              "note": "A forever-actor announcement robbed — Denzel, one of our all-timers, taken from Pacino (who has Godfather II anyway)."
            },
            {
              "title": "The Grand Budapest Hotel",
              "year": 2014,
              "category": "Best Director Winner Snub",
              "note": "Wes Anderson's coronation moment that just passed him by — taken from Iñárritu's Birdman."
            },
            {
              "title": "The Dark Knight",
              "year": 2008,
              "category": "Best Picture Nominee Snub (21st c.)",
              "note": "The snub that triggered the Academy's Best Picture expansion — 'and then I don't have to hear about it anymore.'"
            },
            {
              "title": "Bringing Up Baby",
              "year": 1938,
              "category": "Best Picture Nominee Snub (20th c.)",
              "note": "Zero nominations for a signature screwball that invents the whole genre."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "host": "Chris Ryan",
          "picks": [
            {
              "title": "Goodfellas",
              "year": 1990,
              "category": "Best Picture Winner Snub",
              "note": "Over Dances with Wolves — the most egregious one; Scorsese then waited 16 years for The Departed."
            },
            {
              "title": "2001: A Space Odyssey",
              "year": 1968,
              "category": "Best Picture Nominee Snub (20th c.)",
              "note": "Kubrick, criminally overlooked — never topped as science fiction."
            },
            {
              "title": "All About Eve",
              "year": 1950,
              "category": "Best Actress Winner Snub",
              "note": "Bette Davis — one of CR's five favorite performances ever, over Judy Holliday."
            },
            {
              "title": "The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo",
              "year": 2011,
              "category": "Best Picture Nominee Snub (21st c.)",
              "note": "Into one of the worst nominee slates ever — 'closer to Fincher every day.'"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "host": "Sean Fennessey",
          "picks": [
            {
              "title": "Singin' in the Rain",
              "year": 1952,
              "category": "Best Picture Nominee Snub (20th c.)",
              "note": "Should have won outright — take out The Greatest Show on Earth entirely."
            },
            {
              "title": "The Last Detail",
              "year": 1973,
              "category": "Best Actor Winner Snub",
              "note": "Give Nicholson his 1973 (from Jack Lemmon, who already had one) — a domino chain that ends with the slap never happening."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "host": "Katie Rich",
          "picks": [
            {
              "title": "Brokeback Mountain",
              "year": 2005,
              "category": "Best Picture Winner Snub",
              "note": "Maybe the worst Best Picture win of all time (Crash) — a chalk pick that had to be done."
            },
            {
              "title": "Do the Right Thing",
              "year": 1989,
              "category": "Best Picture Nominee Snub (20th c.)",
              "note": "The be-all, end-all Spike Lee snub — taken over When Harry Met Sally."
            },
            {
              "title": "Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind",
              "year": 2004,
              "category": "Best Actress Winner Snub",
              "note": "Kate Winslet, overdue — a chain that eventually frees Glenn Close for Albert Nobbs."
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
